      "year": 2018,
      "abstract": "to a transcendent realm of timeless truth, elevated beyond the pluralism of opinions held by citizens in the polis, why did he write Socratic dialogues? One could make a similar judgment about the Socratic character of the task of political philosophy as sketched in Book I, chapters 4\u20135 of theNicomachean Ethics. Reflecting on this might require us to rethink Arendt\u2019s mythology of a philosophical tradition that is monological rather than dialogical. Arendtian politics is a politics of exuberant participatory citizenship. Faithful Arendtians like Zerilli will tend to presume that the expansion of civic agency and the lively exchange of opinions will always bring enhanced democracy. All committed democrats will naturally find this an attractive presumption. But is this vision not shadowed by lurking doubts? Contemporary populism should give us pause. Nigel Farage worked hard to disseminate his strong opinions and invested tremendous exertions of civic agency in his project to sever the UK from the European Union. Does that automatically mean that his politics should be welcomed and applauded by a theory of \u201cjudging politically\u201d? Can we afford to abstract from the content of the politics? Zerilli wants \u201ca critical practice of judging as rooted in the exchange of . . . perspectives\u201d that are not prevetted by a proceduralist normative theory (p. 269; cf. pp. 132 and 141). But what ensures that the outcome is \u201ccritical\u201d rather than reactionary? This problem also links up with similar difficulties with respect to another central pillar of Zerilli\u2019s effort to appropriate Arendtian theorizing for an ambitious rethinking of contemporary democracy, namely, Arendt\u2019s conception of pluralism: \u201cFor Arendt, to belong to a democratic political community is to have a \u2018common world,\u2019 not to share a worldview, and this common world exists only where there is a plurality of worldviews. Our sense of what is common . . . can appear only when it is seen from multiple perspectives\u201d (p. 265). But this Arendtian pluralism may be less open-ended than either Arendt or Zerilli wish it to be. Is the common world upheld or undermined, for instance, by a worldview that privileges consumer choices over commitment to shared citizenship? Or that prefers to lower taxes even if it means a diminished public realm? Is it upheld or undermined by a worldview that regards the purposes of secular politics as paltry compared with the imperatives of religious piety? Most dramatically: is it upheld or undermined by the racist worldview of the contemporary Alt Right? Zerilli clearly believes that Arendt\u2019s politics of judgment is recommended by its superior accommodation of moral and political pluralism, certainly relative to reigning forms of contemporary liberalism that are confident in their grasp of a definitive moral truth. But Arendt\u2019s political philosophy, with its celebration of participatory citizenship, its privileging of immortality over eternity, and its moral universalism, also champions a fairly well-defined worldview (it is hard to imagine that it would count as a political philosophy if it did not)\u2014a worldview that may not be deferred to by some of the plural perspectives that it seeks to encompass. There are surely worldviews that have no interest in contributing to or helping to constitute a common world of the kind imagined by Arendt. Her supposedly open-ended pluralism is, in fact, a pluralism of opinions and perspectives held by those already robustly committed to a shared and jointly constituted public world. This would seem to be an inescapable paradox of pluralism as conceived by Arendt, one that a philosophy built on Arendtian foundations will not easily circumvent. As this discussion illustrates, it is not so easy to appeal to plurality and pluralistic freedom without a philosophical privileging of a particular conception of what normatively defines the common world. What we encounter here is perhaps the Arendtian version of the metaphysical neutralism rightly criticized by Zerilli in other political philosophers (that is, the presumption that one is not oneself relying upon some philosophical Archimedean point). One has to welcome the fact that appeals to truth loom larger in Zerilli\u2019s current version of her theory and her revised interpretation of Arendt than was the case with her earlier work (namely, Zerilli\u2019s important article, \u201cWe Feel Our Freedom\u201d, Political Theory, 33(2), 2005). Yet one still has to wonder whether the new version sufficiently acknowledges that even a theory celebrating the space of judgment as a space of freedom and plurality reposes on a specific claim to philosophical truth and not merely the opinions of citizens transmuted into truths. In other words, however determined one may be to limit truth to \u201cSocratic\u201dmaieutics, a \u201cPlatonic\u201d commitment to the truth of one\u2019s own political philosophy will inevitably creep in.",
